column7: ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Making Content You Enjoy (That Also Gets Views)
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôve had a good start to the week üôè

I wanted to spend a little time today talking about that age-old
question or dilemma that all creators face when thinking about
content which is best encapsulated in what I like to call the
Venn Diagram Dilemma of Content Creation - the name needs a
little work üòÖ

Let me explain.

Whenever my team and I brainstorm new videos, we're frequently
coming up against the issue of my excitement levels for a given
idea. Fundamentally, if I'm not enthused by the prospect of
creating a video (even if there's strong evidence that it's
worked elsewhere for other creators, or perhaps a similar concept
has worked for us in the past), it's hard to really get excited
about the prospect of filming.

And I've actually noticed this more and more over the last couple
of years - my bar for feeling excited about filming has
definitely gone up which is perhaps why I've published less
content but also reflects the direction of the content on the
channel too.

For example, I know that if I made a video titled, ‚ÄúHow To Make
Passive Income as a Student in 2025‚Äù, it would probably get a
million views‚ÄîI‚Äôve got little doubt about that. I still have
students in my audience, it's a big target market, the title is
super clickable, and so it'd probably perform well.

But with videos like this, they don‚Äôt excite me anymore because
I‚Äôm no longer targeting my content at students and it feels like
I‚Äôm just making content for the algorithm.

Trust me, every single YouTuber and content creator faces this
same exact problem‚Äîfiguring out how to make stuff that both
excites you and performs well. ü§î

In my head, I think of it like a Venn diagram. On one side,
you‚Äôve got the stuff you want to make. And on the other, you‚Äôve
got what ‚Äúthe audience‚Äù wants to see.

‚Äã
Now I say ‚Äúaudience‚Äù in quotation marks because the algorithm is
basically the audience, as the YouTube team themselves say all
the time. If your video is sufficiently intriguing for a large
enough group of people to click, and sufficiently good for them
to actually watch, it‚Äôll do well.

Content is king, as they say. üëë

It‚Äôs also worth pointing out that the ‚Äúaudience‚Äù is always a bit
of a mystery. We‚Äôve now got over 6 million subscribers on the
channel, but loads of them probably haven‚Äôt watched a video of
mine in years. So we don‚Äôt know exactly who ‚Äúthe audience‚Äù really
is. But there‚Äôs definitely a category of content that resonates
more widely‚Äîand that‚Äôs what the YouTube algorithm picks up on.

In an ideal world, the stuff you want to make would be exactly
the kind of stuff your audience wants to watch. There would be
this big juicy overlap between the two circles of the Venn
diagram.

‚Äã
But most YouTubers don‚Äôt have this perfect overlap‚ÄîI certainly
don‚Äôt.

For instance, I recently had this idea for a video about mimetic
desire that Luke Burgis talks about in his book, Wanting.

Super interesting concept, but the the question is, how do I make
the average viewer intrigued by the idea? How do I package this
idea so that it drives more clicks?

If you‚Äôve been following the channel, you‚Äôd have noticed that we
actually released this video on Friday but it‚Äôs currently sitting
at 9 out of 10 (i/e performing very poorly for us) which raises
questions about whether the video falls outside of the Venn
diagram overlap or, alternatively, we‚Äôve just got the packaging
wrong (or both - let me know what you think).

At the end of the day, even though the circles in my Venn diagram
will never fully overlap, I know that part of the game I signed
up for is figuring out how to make videos I‚Äôm proud of‚Ä¶that also
perform well.

And part of the reason for writing about it in this email is to
let you know that you‚Äôre not alone if you also struggle with this
balance. I‚Äôve seen plenty of students in PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/v8ukg7rvwltrhv46v3kbghv4xx8llh9/48hvh7ump5pd9gbq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXZlbm5kaWFncmFtX2FwcjkmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) have the same dilemmas, whether they‚Äôre beginners figuring out
their niche or more established creators facing idea dilemmas
like the ones I‚Äôve talked about here.

If you‚Äôre looking for a more practical piece of advice, one of
the tricks I‚Äôve found helpful recently is to imagine myself
giving a lecture at university. This forces me to ask the
question - if I had to teach this topic, what would I say to make
it more exciting?

This simple reframe has managed to get me over multiple creative
blocks and it‚Äôs these kind of mental gymnastics that I still rely
on to help me continue to enjoy the process of creating.
Otherwise, I fall into the trap of thinking: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm just back on
the hamster wheel. Just making stuff for the algorithm‚Äù and no
creator wants to feel this way üòÖ

I‚Äôd love to know what your Venn diagram looks like and if you‚Äôve
ever felt this tension in your own creative work. Hit reply and
let me know üíå

Otherwise have a great week and we'll speak soon :)

Ali xx

column7: Ever feel like you‚Äôre living ‚Äúthe wrong life‚Äù?
column9:
Hey Candace,

¬†

Have you ever found yourself thinking you were doing everything ‚Äúright‚Äù‚Ä¶

¬†

‚Ä¶but yet feeling like everything was wrong and you were somehow out of place?¬†

¬†

That‚Äôs exactly where Marcia found herself a few years ago.

¬†

She had a great job.

She‚Äôd hit all her salary goals.

¬†

Yet she still felt completely empty.

Her life looked exactly the way it was supposed to.

¬†

And yet, something felt deeply wrong about it.

¬†

In this new video ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gGm90Qo24cg&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+170-5&utm_content_name=Ever+feel+like+you%E2%80%99re+living+%E2%80%9Cthe+wrong+life%E2%80%9D%3F&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ), Marcia is getting on camera to talk honestly about her story and the moment that cracked everything open for her.

¬†

Plus, she‚Äôll share the three life-changing shifts she made that helped her reconnect with what really mattered.¬†

¬†

So you can bring your life back into alignment too - and replace the meaningless, with joy and purpose.¬†

¬†

The Brief V2 (1) (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWtvp94d0TDnW5pwPx-1J3jJqW6wcfC_5DMkDRN1f4_XH3l5QzW6N1vHY6lZ3kXW1Z-Ymc7gyR05W7Hf6Yk6Qss4lW20zjPY8hVM4LW1GBCbv758mKgW4Ps7WR1JX3sdW2wcV9D4t-3QSW2YCtLn3-Vln4VDC46y8YJ4NkVyJxK98FXTWVW3ZxCBr6KB4YWW370MSc6D6NxjN8qW61R89gRQW6SK6Cv3lV375N1Hf48DLvZ22W5dQStZ8y6DpjV5_9nG39vCt_W1C-wXH8gd8y1Vz_c9v873J1yW9cKkFv885Fz0W3Q7scZ6nzx7mW7qp4CF818T24V_2gt56Y8cGvf69z6Vz04 )

Articles, ideas, and news about UX/UI design and related spaces.

üì∞ 3 THINGS TO CHECK OUT

Audit Your Designs with ChatGPT (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWtvp94d0TDnW5pwPx-1J3jJqW6wcfC_5DMkDRN1f4_X-3l5QzW7lCdLW6lZ3nMW5rgW3t5ghF9RW48ML6p8mfGBPV5wHZg7_vDYbW3mdWbQ6qYsQXW3CNdmx94xhDqW1FwGG02pTk-ZW84d04l8zFS5TN1cfXPsGNz6YVGJDgj2lZVk9W3jh6Kb1fk5bkN10B81jJL4fLF7vY9Yn1CybW9477c-13XcnhW54FCL77217rtW8k9gLS39gTrpW97B1xM2GXGTGW5q-phv4NDzQzW4yX8tR1lBnCtW2p3NS94l_QPFW91mwy_9hkVLYW6XGsdc3p3T9kVGzFmY1vSH-WW6gpRL28KC_GfW3MwBDf4VKPVff2kw7ZP04 )

- Product design Nick Babich breaks down how designers can use ChatGPT-5 to conduct structured UX audits‚Äîanalyzing screenshots, identifying heuristic issues, and generating improvement ideas with guided prompts.

- Babich stresses the importance of giving ChatGPT clear, structured prompts to avoid generic results and using its feedback as a starting point‚Äîsupplemented with real user testing to uncover deeper, context-specific issues.

- ‚ÄúDesign audit is a general term that product teams use when they‚Äôre talking about evaluating design according to a certain criterion. I propose a general workflow for design audit [using AI] that will cover essential steps.‚Äù

Apple's Liquid Glass is Cracked (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWtvp94d0TDnW5pwPx-1J3jJqW6wcfC_5DMkDRN1f4_XH3l5QzW6N1vHY6lZ3lzW1bkcB_7f41f7W7FXr_C8R7PJsW3gsrK98szYKdW1sJtcF2G1mxdW1rqNJC8m8DQyW5QmDfR51xjbBW7HHvkC6v9pkQW4lHWQW89Lq3gW3HnVCc22WLfyN1wG_jXp2mB3M_J7NDbH2nrW7klnj-9lG7HdW1-7Jlr3SbnpzW5_9vDq8_9jZfW596d9838kkVdW6tFWX375b1dVW8bmrPT3dLXZ0W1FJLXS39P8SSW8gwgSt30M6BSW34f5Fd6n6Vr6W6kQ7zK69H6x_Vp-kYV79dPHPdJ7cT804 )

- Senior UX Director Raluca Budiu critiques Apple‚Äôs new ‚ÄúLiquid Glass‚Äù design, which introduces shimmering, translucent visuals and fluid motion‚Äîbut often at the expense of clarity and usability.

- Budiu argues that these effects make text harder to read, buttons less predictable, and navigation more confusing‚Äîsignaling a shift toward aesthetics over accessibility and consistency in Apple‚Äôs design language.

- ‚ÄúOne of the oldest findings in usability is that anything placed on top of something else becomes harder to see. Yet here we are, in 2025, with Apple proudly obscuring text, icons, and controls by making them transparent and placing them on top of busy backgrounds.‚Äù

The Grayscale Problem  (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWtvp94d0TDnW5pwPx-1J3jJqW6wcfC_5DMkDRN1f4_X-3l5QzW7lCdLW6lZ3mFW80lcj71S29RtW87dQ1Q1p1PGQN6Bkfm8sZSnnW5Y_R-G5L_vxxW2hT1nw5Vnt5gW8KCJ1t3qD_DRW8yvy6w4M8nQxW502y2Q42VkrXW2VT5mQ3nj2RlW6lSJjr3cz-7NN31t3HYtdP8jW85sS-P65C0DVW7ZYg0y38_HMbW2cdfnK6QfvvTN86L8dtPVrGcW6L3g8D3KNdbpW8QM36Z3cdyjFW3dMRT526SRbvVh6Dwp8H9FHPW14S_-6554_YjW38j0py4QyCQ2W4yC-8V4xDb9pW5lyX2X4wL7PQW8XZ_ph8chvbnf4VswNz04 )

- Software developer Frederick O‚ÄôBrien examines current design trends, finding that the web is increasingly conforming to safe, minimal, and monochromatic patterns driven by optimization and market pressures‚Äîoften at the expense of creativity and variety.

- He warns that an overreliance on tools like templates and generative AI is reducing experimentation and variety‚Äîrisking a web that becomes bland and grayscale unless designers and creators intentionally push back.

- ‚ÄúThe web is a flexible enough domain that I think it belongs in the realm of architecture. A city where all buildings look alike has a soul-crushing quality about it. The same is true, I think, of the web.‚Äù

üíú PORTFOLIO INSPIRATION

Juliann Mapletoft (https://hs.designlab.com/e3t/Ctc/UD+113/d56t7h04/VWtvp94d0TDnW5pwPx-1J3jJqW6wcfC_5DMkDRN1f4_Xn3l5QzW69sMD-6lZ3pKW6s-d5B1D8ChYW1rfqjb4xZ1SHW7kkP2x7w7H29N3lMbs8Ql1ClW8xXQfn6r9zD6W6s6Fm64rFGY7W3zk_FJ4YfqDwW52qRDH3jVb6cW2GS-mx8414zCW6wq2h258VGsgW3WCzRy54McF1W6mKhHs3fKb4lW7HTpLp1-N0JCW45XSPF3RNDnLN3bCbKt6Z3HZW3nk3Gr7f-p41W5sjSz134dX1DW6CyX_B5cQtRnW5cr7785TPGdmW1b68pH8YmjXSf9k_GZP04 ) , a UX Academy graduate, brings a clean, functional, and empathetic approach to her work. In New Leaf, a mental health mobile app, she designs a calm and supportive experience that encourages users to prioritize well-being through intuitive navigation and thoughtful visual balance. Her Wish Boutique responsive redesign transforms the online shopping experience with refined aesthetics, clear information architecture, and a focus on seamless usability‚Äîreflecting her commitment to creating reliable, human-centered digital products.

column7: Clicks are clues! Tag your audience based on email link clicks
column9:
Hi there, 
 Podia Email has built-in segmentation tools to help you track your audience‚Äôs interests, purchases, and activity. But here‚Äôs a pro tip: you can get even more specific by tagging subscribers based on the links they click in your emails. 
 Here are a few smart ways to use link click tags: 
 - Follow up with interested leads: Tag people who click to learn more about a product, then follow up if they don‚Äôt purchase. 
- Learn what topics your audience cares about: Add different tags for different topics you cover, then track which ones get the most clicks over time. 
- Let people opt out of a campaign (without unsubscribing from your whole list): For example, add a tag to a link that says ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt send me more emails about XYZ.‚Äù Then use that tag as an exit condition to remove them from the campaign. 
 To set this up in Podia, start by opening the Podia Email editor and adding your content. 
 Highlight your link, click ‚ÄúLink,‚Äù then hit the ‚ÄúTag people‚Äù button. 
 Create or choose your tags, then hit "Save." 
 [Image "Tagging+links+in+emails.png?expires=1759300074&signature=c07928c9253f38dc6f9a189e0533db4c2341b25adeb2a131f9a4d8515b67d6c5&req=dSQhEs96lYNbWfMW2XS%2FiVzroERy%2Bn4RhIxzh0biTJmltbDYLyA%3D%0A"] 
 



 
 You can also tag link clicks on images and buttons. 
 Need a step-by-step walkthrough? Check out this quick help doc. 
 Happy emailing, 
 Spencer from Podia 
 P.S. For more email goodness, learn how to build a successful (and profitable) email newsletter in this guide!

Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôre having a good day.

We‚Äôve just wrapped up quarterly planning on our team offsite here
in Hong Kong - it‚Äôs always nice to work with the team in-person
like this, we always come away with a greater sense of clarity
for the months ahead.

We‚Äôve been doing these quarterly offsites for a couple of years
now - each time reviewing our 3-year vision for the company, our
annual goals and then planning the next 90 days on a more
granular level.

Looking forward like this - imagining what you want that future
state to look like - isn‚Äôt just important in business, it matters
on a personal level too.

Just fast forward one year to April 2nd 2026.

We‚Äôre 365 days further forward in your own life.

What do you imagine you‚Äôve achieved by that point?

Did you follow through on the goals you set at the Spring Reset?

If you‚Äôre anything like me, it can be difficult to put yourself
in that space - sometimes it‚Äôs hard to predict what‚Äôs going to
happen next week üòÖ

But it‚Äôs important to imagine what the path to that future state
looks like so that you can align your daily, weekly and monthly
actions to make sure you‚Äôre heading in the right direction.

That was the whole point of doing the future-facing exercises on
Saturday during the Spring Reset to ensure that you‚Äôre able to
stay aligned and take consistent action towards your goals. (If
you missed it, you can still access the recording here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/0vu4o3k67va9h9xep2qhlhvleex55hn/6qhehoulkeq942f9/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2NvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi9zcHJpbmctcmVzZXQtd29ya3Nob3AtcmV3YXRjaC1jb25maXJtYXRpb24v
)).

Similar questions were being asked this time last year by
students signing up to LifeOS Pro - or Productivity Lab as it was
called then - and some of them have seen incredible
transformations over the past 12 months of being part of the
community.

Take Frida who dreamed of building her own business and YouTube
channel, but her demanding corporate role had left her feeling
drained. LifeOS Pro offered her a structured approach to
rebuilding her focus and clarity. Eight months later, Frida had
left her corporate job to build her own company and by applying
the Lab‚Äôs principle of ‚Äúfocusing on one thing that moves you
forward,‚Äù she‚Äôs making steady progress without burning out.

Or take Zaim who‚Äôs biggest challenge was finding the
accountability and structured time he needed to truly level up
his side business. That accountability came quickly through
LifeOS Pro‚Äôs daily Focus Labs which enabled him to establish a
rhythm, showing up every morning and even late at night when
needed. This intense commitment led to incredible progress. In
just six weeks, his income from his side hustle doubled, and by
the end of two months, he was consistently bringing in five
figures monthly. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs the accountability. Setting goals each
session and knowing others were with me on the journey‚Äîit changed
everything.‚Äù

Frida and Zaim didn‚Äôt have some sort of secret code to
productivity, they just leveraged the spaces and accountability
provided by the community to regularly reflect on their vision
and build a system to take consistent daily actions that compound
into those longer-term transformations.

If you want to follow in their footsteps and invest in achieving
your goals, click here (

) to sign up to LifeOS Pro.

And if you feel like you don‚Äôt need the accountability but you

And if you think you‚Äôve got everything in hand when it comes to

If you were forwarded this message, you can sign up to receive the free daily email [here](https://news.jayshetty.me/?utm_source=news.jayshetty.me&utm_medium=newsletter&utm_campaign=fresh-look-same-purpose&last_resource_guid=Post%3A4adba504-528c-49a4-98a8-d39ab3060dba&jwt_token=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.eyJzdWJzY3JpYmVyX2lkIjoiZjdjNzNmM2YtZjc3Zi00ZDhlLWFiYzctYWU0MjEzOTMwNTVkIiwicHVibGljYXRpb25faWQiOiI0MDUwODUwMi1kM2E0LTQ3ZGEtOTgxYS00NDAxMzEyYWQwZGUiLCJhY2Nlc3NfdHlwZSI6InJlYWQtb25seSIsImV4cCI6MTc2MTkzOTQ1MSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcHAuYmVlaGlpdi5jb20iLCJpYXQiOjE3NjE3NjY2NTF9.fpEW02IXWjBphCNx9yZe6sNAzlznSe7gnWomsQcIn_c).

View image: (https://media.beehiiv.com/cdn-cgi/image/fit=scale-down,format=auto,onerror=redirect,quality=80/uploads/asset/file/5f7ff68c-d0d9-4719-967e-541b8fd386d6/DW-Newsletter-Quote__8_.png?t=1762804863)
Caption: 


--------------------
# Q: Why can one bad moment overshadow an entirely good day?

A friend of mine used to work at a sleepaway summer camp. And he told us about the scary stories he used to tell the campers. Some of those stories would‚Äôve kept _me_ awake all night. I can‚Äôt even imagine what it would be like to listen to them as a kid.¬†

So I asked him, How did you get away with all that? Wouldn‚Äôt the kids tell their parents? He shrugged his shoulders and said, _‚ÄúSimple. We gave all the kids popsicles on the day their parents picked them up, and they went home happy.‚Äù_

It sounds really simple, and kind of silly. But my friend was onto something. Let me explain.

In 1993, the [Nobel prize-winning psychologist Daniel Kahneman](https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/economic-sciences/2002/kahneman/facts/) and his colleagues published a study called ‚Äú[When More Pain is Preferred to Less](https://www.jstor.org/stable/40062570).‚Äù **It outlines an ingenious experiment that went something like this:**

Participants put their hands in painfully cold water for 60 seconds. Then, in a second trial, they put their hand in the same painfully cold water for 90 seconds. Except for the second time, for the final 30 seconds, the temperature was raised just a little bit. It was still painful, but just _not quite _as painful.

Which trial do you think sounds worse?

Logically, it would be the second one, right? Because the painful cold is experienced for longer. Well, it turns out people rated the second trial as better. 

But why?

According to [Kahneman](https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/economic-sciences/2002/kahneman/facts/), we don‚Äôt judge experiences by their average or total duration. We judge experiences based on 2 moments:

1) The peak, or the most intense part (good _or_ bad)
2) The end

So if you think back to that _awful_ vacation you took, you remember the day it got so hot you couldn‚Äôt do anything (the peak) and that miserable 16-hour flight home (the end). Even though there was a lot of other vacation time that wasn‚Äôt so bad.

Or if you think about that _amazing_ week you had last month, you remember the promotion you got at work (the peak) and the party you had that Friday to celebrate it (the end). Even though some pretty annoying stuff happened, also.

The [Peak-End rule](https://www.psychologytoday.com/ca/blog/automatic-you/202109/peak-end-rule) reveals how one cruel goodbye can ruin a relationship. And one kind act at the end of someone‚Äôs life can heal decades of distance. We don‚Äôt carry the full record. We carry the peak. And the ending.

[It‚Äôs one of the biggest lessons I learned last year.](https://youtu.be/iVqdj_HZ03U)¬†

# Today‚Äôs Wiser Choice

It‚Äôs one thing to learn about how the brain works. It‚Äôs another to act on that information. 

Now that you know that humans really only hold onto the peaks and ends of experiences, how should that change your behavior?

**Try This**: Take out your calendar or your to-do list. In the coming month, are there things you can do to maximize the [peaks and ends](https://www.psychologytoday.com/ca/blog/automatic-you/202109/peak-end-rule) of your experiences?

For example, maybe you‚Äôre giving a presentation at work. Is there a way you can end on a bang? And maybe have a great moment right in the middle?

Or maybe you‚Äôre planning a trip with your family. Can you plan for a really big, fun day in the middle? And end on a high note?

Reply to this email and tell me what you plan to do this month to maximize the Peak-End rule. I read every response, and can‚Äôt wait to read yours.

column7: How to Set Up Your Student Account at CUNY SPS
column9:
Dear Candace,
 
To register for classes at CUNY SPS, you will need to set up your student account in CUNYfirst <https://home.cunyfirst.cuny.edu/>. This is the system that you will use to register for classes, view your class schedule and financial aid, and much more.
                                   
To access your account, please visit the CUNYfirst Log-In page at https://home.cunyfirst.cuny.edu and follow the instructions below: 
	 For First-time Users: Activate Your Account <https://www.cuny.edu/about/administration/offices/cis/cuny-login-faq/#CUNY_Login_Documents>
	 For Returning Users: Forgot Your Password? <https://www.cuny.edu/about/administration/offices/cis/cuny-login-faq/#CUNY_Login_Documents>

Please note if you were assigned an identification number by the Admissions office because you did not have a social security number at the time of application, you will need to use this number in lieu of a social security number while setting up your CUNYfirst account. Please contact Office of Admissions at admissions@sps.cuny.edu if you need your identification number again.

                  Once you activate your CUNYfirst account, you will be able to register for classes during the registration period. For detailed instructions on how to register, please visit the Student Self Service <https://www.cuny.edu/about/administration/offices/cis/cunyfirst/training/students/#1446666384637-3a90ba9e-7400> page and click on the link titled "Enrollment".

                  Please note that some programs require advisement prior to registration. For questions about advisement and registration, please contact your program advisor <https://engage.sps.cuny.edu/register/programadvisorslist>. 

If you experience any technical difficulty while activating your account, please contact the Help Desk at helpdesk@sps.cuny.edu and include your EMPLID number: 10878863
                  

                  Please be advised that if you have a hold on your account from a previous CUNY campus, you will not be able to register. The hold must be resolved in order for you to move forward in selecting your classes for the upcoming term.

I wish you all the best for a successful educational experience at the CUNY School of Professional Studies.

                Sincerely,

                Lucas J. Sifuentes
    Assistant Dean & Chief Enrollment Management Officer
The CUNY School of Professional Studies is regionally accredited through the Middle States Commission on Higher Education. 
119 West 31st Street | New York, NY 10001

ü§î 5 Quotes I‚Äôve been Reflecting on & Book Recommendations
column9:
Hey Candace,

Last week, I asked y‚Äôall for some book series recommendations.
Big thank you to the 200 of you who replied, with 164 different
series recommendations. At the bottom of this email, I‚Äôve listed
the top 10, in case you‚Äôre looking for some fiction
recommendations :)

Anyway, I don‚Äôt feel like I have anything useful to say this week
lol, so in addition to the book recommendations below, here are 5
quotes from various sources that I‚Äôve been reflecting on recently
üëá

1 - From Meditations for Mortals (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/wnh2h6uq460x8zfl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL21lZGl0YXRpb25zZm9ybW9ydGFscw==
) by Oliver Burkeman

Many people these days report the feeling that they begin each
morning in a kind of ‚Äòproductivity debt‚Äô, which they must
struggle to pay off over the course of the day, in hopes of
returning to a zero balance by the time evening comes. If they
fail ‚Äì or worse, don‚Äôt even try ‚Äì it‚Äôs as though they haven‚Äôt
quite justified their existence on the planet. If this describes
you, there‚Äôs a good chance that like me you belong to the gloomy
bunch psychologists label ‚Äòinsecure overachievers‚Äô, which is a
diplomatic way of saying that our accomplishments, impressive as
they may sometimes be, are driven ultimately by feelings of
inadequacy.
2 - From Die with Zero (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/reh8h9um7z6wk9b6/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3pRNlA=
) by Bill Perkins, referencing The Top 5 Regrets of the Dying (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/08hwhgu2xrlgnoap/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1ZFb0lL
) by palliative care nurse Bronnie Ware

Along those lines, the second regret‚Äîand actually the top regret
among Ware‚Äôs male patients‚Äîwas this: ‚ÄúI wish I had not worked so
hard.‚Äù That hits right at the heart of what I‚Äôm preaching. ‚ÄúAll
of the men I nursed deeply regretted spending so much of their
lives on the treadmill of a work existence,‚Äù Ware writes. Women
had this regret, too, but, as Ware points out, her patients were
from an older generation, when fewer women worked outside the
home. And when people say they regret working so hard, they are
not talking about the hard work of raising children; they are
talking about working to make a living to pay the bills and, as a
result, missing ‚Äútheir children‚Äôs youth and their partner‚Äôs
companionship.‚Äù
3 - From The Second Mountain (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/8ghqh3uo3nrqw2bl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1FjNFBDMg==
) by David Brooks

The natural tendency is to put oneself at the center of any
activity. To ask, How am I doing? That question is fine to ask
once. But it becomes paralyzing if you ask it all the time. A
pitcher who is thinking about how he is pitching cannot pitch
well. His focus is on self, not the task. ‚ÄúIn any hard
discipline, whether it be gardening, structural engineering, or
Russian,‚Äù the philosopher and motorcycle mechanic Matthew
Crawford writes, ‚Äúone submits to things that have their own
intractable ways.‚Äù
4 - From How to Live on 24 Hours a Day (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/vqh3hmuo4rwem4hw/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1J0NEM=
) by Arnold Bennett. This quote is the ultimate secret to time
management, on how to make time to do all the things you need to
(and want to) do:

I have found no such wonderful secret. Nor do I expect to find
it, nor do I expect that anyone else will ever find it. It is
undiscovered. When you first began to gather my drift, perhaps
there was a resurrection of hope in your breast. Perhaps you said
to yourself, ‚ÄúThis man will show me an easy, unfatiguing way of
doing what I have so long in vain wished to do.‚Äù Alas, no! The
fact is that there is no easy way, no royal road. The path to
Mecca is extremely hard and stony, and the worst of it is that
you never quite get there after all.
The most important preliminary to the task of arranging one‚Äôs
life so that one may live fully and comfortably within one‚Äôs
daily budget of twenty-four hours is the calm realisation of the
extreme difficulty of the task, of the sacrifices and the endless
effort which it demands. I cannot too strongly insist on this.
5 - From Good Work (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/l2heh6ul47x6qvag/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3dNeHdr
) by Paul Millerd

Good work doesn‚Äôt usually happen on a factory schedule and often
has a natural seasonality. But when you stop doing it, good work
seduces you back. It is something you must do. Once you discover
your good work, take it seriously and protect it, as it can be
one of the most powerful ways to show up in the world,
contribute, and feel useful.
Now to the book recommendations.

These were the most recommended, along with some of my own notes.

* ‚ÄãThe Kingkiller Chronicles Series (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/m2h7h6u39z4m27il/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3Qyelo=
) by Patrick Rothfuss - Recommended by 9 people. I read books 1+2
back in like 2018, and have been waiting patiently (like the rest
of the fanbase) for book 3 for what seems like forever. I‚Äôd
actually kinda recommend you not start this series until the
third book comes out though‚Ä¶
* ‚ÄãEragon (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/dphehmueknp8d7fl/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2VyYWdvbg==
) by Christopher Paolini - Recommended by 4 people. Banger series
that I remember reading way back when I was a teenager. I haven‚Äôt
read the latest installation Murtagh just yet though, so that‚Äôll
be soon on my reading list :)
* ‚ÄãThrone Of Glass (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/e0hph0u7eorqmkf7/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1U0alA=
) series by Sarah J. Maas - Recommended by 4 people. I bought the
set in paperback a few years ago, thinking ‚Äúooh these look really
pretty‚Äù but never actually read any of them. Given the glowing
recommendations, guess it‚Äôll have to be the next series I read.
* ‚ÄãThe Lord of the Rings (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/7qh7h2u985nwdoc9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1BrUGlnUmc=
) by JRR Tolkien - Recommended by 4 people. This is one of those
series where I‚Äôm like: ‚Äúyep there‚Äôs no excuse for why I haven‚Äôt
read this yet‚Äù. I tried Fellowship a bunch of times over the
years, but kept getting stuck on the Tom Bombadil stuff. Then I
listened to some of the audiobook and got beyond that point, but
fell off around Rivendell. Might be time to resume.

Then we had a few different series that were recommended by 3
people each:

* Wheel of Time by Robert Jordan (with the final 3 books written
by Brandon Sanderson after Robert Jordan‚Äôs death) - I read this
around 2018-2020 and would definitely recommend. It gets super
slow about halfway through the series, but it‚Äôs totally worth
pushing through the pain of those middle books to get to the
final few.
* ‚ÄãBeartown (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/owhkhwuwndqgxwbq/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3k5Z1l4VGc=
) by Frederick Backman - never heard of this, will add to the
list.
* ‚ÄãHunger Games (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/z2hgh7ue7xlp5piz/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL09kNE5VZw==
) by Suzanne Collins - obviously incredible, loved the original
trilogy when I was in school, and loved the first prequel a few
years ago, and currently listening to Sunrise on the Reaping on
Audible
* ‚ÄãGentlemen Bastard Series (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/p8hehqu4doqgrxur/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL2R5YXlhdzQ=
) by Scott Lynch - I‚Äôve heard this recommended over the years but
never tried it, the name always sort-of put me off, making me
think: ‚Äúoh it doesn‚Äôt sound like a ‚Äòserious‚Äô series‚Äù but given
the recommendations from y‚Äôall, guess it‚Äôll have to go on the
list.
* ‚ÄãThe Poppy War (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6lzegwh5iz5d6d33cw/x0hph3uez0q9kxtg/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL3lJb0E=
) by R.F. Kuang - Never heard of it, will add to the list.

Big thank you to everyone who replied to last week‚Äôs email with
book recommendations :)

And apologies for no real ‚Äúcontent‚Äù from me this week - if you‚Äôve
reached this point in the email, I hope you got enough value from
the quotes + book recommendations that it‚Äôs been worth your
while. (And just an fyi, some of the links above are affiliate
links).

Have a great week!

Ali xx

‚Äãüí°Stan: Turn Your Ideas into Income (

Hey Candace,

A few weeks ago, I listened to Joe Hudson‚Äôs interview on Chris
Williamson‚Äôs podcast Modern Wisdom (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh29ldooupu47p2pnnh7/z2hgh7uekz4p0lsz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD0xMXMmdj1wOFpoY1lvVzQzcw==
) - and there was a casual comment Joe made that I‚Äôve been
thinking about ever since.

Joe and Chris were talking about money anxiety, the fear of
running out of money etc. To paraphrase, Joe says something like:

A classic high-achiever thing is: ‚ÄúI‚Äôve got to keep hustling
because if I stop, I‚Äôm going to end up broke and homeless.‚Äù
I‚Äôm listening to this thinking: yep that makes sense. I often
feel an underlying anxiety to this effect: I need to grind harder
on the business, because if I don‚Äôt, we might run out of money,
and I‚Äôll end up broke and homeless.

But then he goes on to say:

But you‚Äôre not afraid of being homeless itself. You‚Äôre afraid of
the EMOTIONS that you think you‚Äôll have when you‚Äôre homeless.
Because if I told you ‚Äúyeah you‚Äôre going to be homeless, but
you‚Äôre going to be incredibly happy, the joy you‚Äôll feel will be
amazing, the level of connection you‚Äôll feel will be incredible‚Ä¶‚Äù
all of a sudden, you‚Äôre probably not that scared of being
homeless anymore.
His point (from what I can gather) was that we‚Äôre not afraid of
the situation itself. We‚Äôre afraid of the emotional experience of
the situation.

Btw, I‚Äôm probably not doing this insight justice in the context
of this email, and I‚Äôm sure some people are rolling their eyes:
‚Äúwell actually, being homeless has real physical consequences,
not just emotional ones, not least for yourself but also for your
family etc etc‚Äù.

Even so - there was something in this casual exchange that
massively resonated with me. My thought process went as follows:

Wait a minute. He‚Äôs saying‚Ä¶ I‚Äôm not afraid of the reality of
being homeless. I‚Äôm afraid of what I perceive to be the emotional
consequences of it‚Ä¶

That‚Äôs a hot take‚Ä¶ but okay let‚Äôs try this on for size‚Ä¶ let me
close my eyes, and fully imagine that the business crumbles, and
my YouTube channel no longer gets any views, and I‚Äôve got to lay
the whole team off, and I‚Äôve got no money at all‚Ä¶ and while we‚Äôre
there let‚Äôs say my wife leaves me, takes the kids, and I‚Äôm
saddled with child support payments and alimony etc for the rest
of my life‚Ä¶ so I then declare bankruptcy because I literally have
no money left‚Ä¶ so then I‚Äôm well and truly broke, homeless and
alone‚Ä¶

Okay that would feel pretty bad‚Ä¶ but from what I understand about
emotions, they‚Äôre literally just an internal bodily sensation
accompanied by a thought-based narrative‚Ä¶ so when my mind goes
into ‚Äúuh oh we‚Äôre going to run out of money and end up homeless,
we better hustle harder‚Äù‚Ä¶ the state of ‚Äúbroke and homeless‚Äù that
I‚Äôm so afraid of‚Ä¶ well, that‚Äôs just a set of internal bodily
sensations and accompanying mental narratives‚Ä¶

Huh, that‚Äôs interesting‚Ä¶ so I‚Äôm literally afraid of what I
perceive would be an unpleasant set of internal bodily
sensations‚Ä¶

Huh that doesn‚Äôt seem so bad‚Ä¶ okay let‚Äôs imagine that in this
world where I‚Äôm broke and homeless, I actually feel great, I feel
joyful and happy and super connected to everything‚Ä¶ huh all of a
sudden, I‚Äôm not afraid of going homeless anymore‚Ä¶

**

So that was my thought process as I was listening to the episode,
and I‚Äôve been thinking about it on-and-off since then. Whenever I
find my mind going towards some sort of future-based fear - eg:
the YouTube channel‚Äôs dying, the business is going to crumble,
I‚Äôll run out of money and end up broke etc - I‚Äôve started
shifting my thinking. Instead of reassuring myself with thoughts
like ‚Äúokay that probably won‚Äôt happen‚Äù, or strategising ‚ÄúI‚Äôm
going to make sure that doesn‚Äôt happen by doing XYZ‚Äù (which was
my previous way of dealing with those fears), I‚Äôve instead been
thinking: ‚Äúokay let‚Äôs say that the worst-case scenario DOES
happen, how will I feel then?‚Äù

I‚Äôve been doing my best to really imagine the feelings that I‚Äôm
afraid of‚Ä¶ and within seconds, I realise: ‚Äúoh that‚Äôs not so bad‚Äù.
So then the fear goes away, because I‚Äôve just modelled what the
unpleasant internal bodily sensations are, I‚Äôve realised that I
survived it and it wasn‚Äôt so bad‚Ä¶ so then I‚Äôm not afraid anymore.
And I can then (in theory) make decisions that aren‚Äôt rooted in
fear.

Not sure whether this will ‚Äústick‚Äù, but in the last couple of
weeks, it‚Äôs been an enormously liberating insight that I hadn‚Äôt
previously come across in the world of personal development.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: Last Chance | Join the I School Community
column9:
<https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/data-science/>

Join The I School Community

ACCESS YOUR APPLICATION >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup>
 
Dear Prospective Student,
 
The UC Berkeley School of Information (I School) was created in 1994 to address one of society's most compelling challenges: the need to organize and make sense of the abundance of information that we can now collect, store, and share without regard for cost or distance. The way we organize, represent, govern, and make sense of this information will shape our ability to achieve public as well as private goals.
 
"The I School was created to understand the interaction between people, humans, and digital technology. We were really early movers as the first to launch a master's degree in data science. One of the things that distinguishes our Master of Information and Data Science program is that it is offered online. Not only does it allow people from all over the world to participate, but it really is providing them with an experience of the future of work. What we've learned here is that we can provide very high-quality, very high-touch education online. And that is going to open up access to people all over the world, and it will transform higher education as we know it."
- AnnaLee (Anno) Saxenian
Dean, School of Information
University of California, Berkeley
 
datascience@berkeley draws on the expertise of UC Berkeley's experienced faculty to prepare the next generation of data science leaders from around the world. Watch the video below to hear more about the I School community first hand from both students and faculty.
 
<https://youtu.be/9mPsgHuXA2k>
 
We are now accepting applications for our September 2025 class start. Complete your application >> <https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup> by the final application deadline on Wednesday, May 14.
 
ACCESS YOUR APPLICATION >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup>
 
If you have questions about the Master of Information and Data Science delivered online, please contactel:855-678-6437 or slee2@datascience.berkeley.edu.
 
Sincerely,
 
datascience@berkeley Admissions

column7: üëÄ¬†Key Insights From A Week of Expert Workshops
column9:
Hey Candace,

I hope you‚Äôre having a great week so far üòä

As I mentioned a few weeks ago, we recently hosted five events
over five days within the PTYA Community as part of our first
ever Creator Week - a series of events organised exclusively for
our PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/9qhzhdud3q78zkiz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWNyZWF0b3J3ZWVrXzQmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) members.

It was a fantastic series of sessions, packed full of useful
insights across all kinds of topics from scripting, to product
creation, to growth strategies and I thought I‚Äôd distill just a
couple of the valuable takeaways from each session into this one
email for you to enjoy.

It‚Äôs a bit of a chunky one, but I hope it's worth the read üòÖ

üìù YouTube Scriptwriting
-----------------------

Scripting is a topic I get asked about all the time. Should I
write word for word scripts? What's the best structure? Should I
use a teleprompter? All of these questions are important and so
I've asked George Blackman (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/48hvh7umq5o369fq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ2VvcmdlYmxhY2ttYW4uY29tLw==
) to deliver a series of workshops this year on scripting
specifically, the first of which was during Creator Week.

George has helped some of the largest creators in the world with
their YouTube scripts, including myself and Colin & Samir. He
delivered our first session of the week and talked about how, if
you want to maximise your video retention, you need to think
first and foremost in terms of ‚Äúsegments‚Äù.

‚ÄúOne of the most common problems that I think people have when
they‚Äôre imagining making their next YouTube video, is that they
need to have some incredible revelation that happens at the very
end of the video. They need to be teeing up something that is so
exciting that the viewers physically can‚Äôt help but watch until
the moment that happens at the end. And while that‚Äôs true to an
extent and you do need to have something satisfying at the end of
the video, the satisfaction that viewers get ultimately needs to
come throughout the course of the video. And so before you even
sit down and start writing, you need to start thinking, what are
those little revelations that I‚Äôm going to be able to give my
audience throughout the video [rather than just at the end]?‚Äù
When you break your video down into individual segments, you
avoid the need to have a super grand and flamboyant finale right
at the very end (think Mr Beast). But crucially, according to
George, each segment needs to have these 3 ingredients:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Setup - Tease the mini-payoff to hook your audience e.g.
‚ÄúNext, let‚Äôs talk about one of the biggest productivity-killers
that everyone suffers from, but nobody talks about.‚Äù

2Ô∏è‚É£ Tension - Use stories, interesting data, or a metaphor to
gradually reveal information e.g. ‚ÄúNow, whether we‚Äôve got old
piles of paper lying around on our desks or even just a banana
skin that we‚Äôre too lazy to go to the kitchen and throw away,
it‚Äôs super easy to end up with a messy desk when we‚Äôre busy.‚Äù

3Ô∏è‚É£ Payoff - Deliver the mini-payoff to conclude the segment and
satisfy your viewer‚Äôs curiosity e.g. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs why item number 3 is
having a rubbish bin in every room. It‚Äôll save you time, make
each room tidier, and stop your productivity from halving.‚Äù

ü§ñ Leveraging AI
---------------

I get loads of questions about how to write better prompts, and I
really liked the method Naz - from the YouTube channel Clever
Programmer (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/wnh2h6uqv5zdxvfl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQENsZXZlclByb2dyYW1tZXIvdmlkZW9z
) and co-founder of PoppyAI (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/reh8h9umv28pwec6/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZXRwb3BweS5haQ==
) - shared in the next session - it's SIMPLE... üëá

‚ÄúI have a method called the SIMPLE prompting method‚Ä¶Simple
(language); Instructions (one at a time); Market (who it‚Äôs for).
Patterns (show what ‚Äúgood‚Äù looks like); Language (specify your
tone and voice). External resources, or external knowledge, or
any knowledge that might help the model.‚Äù

Of course, the better your prompts, the better the AI‚Äôs response.
But a lot of people fall into the trap of thinking they need to
write the ‚Äúperfect prompt‚Äù, or create these ‚Äúmega-prompts‚Äù filled
with every single detail under the sun, to get good results.

But that‚Äôs not true.

Instead, you want to treat AI as if you‚Äôre talking to total
beginner. Be specific, and just keep it SIMPLE (sorry if that was
a bit cringey üò¨).

‚ö° Building a YouTube Business
-----------------------------

‚ÄãTintin Smith (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/08hwhgu2wo84g7cp/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGlua2VkaW4uY29tL2luL3RpbnRpbi1zbWl0aC05YjQ3MjAxNzQ=
) was my former YouTuber Producer, as many of you probably know,
and now runs a successful community helping educational content
creators build out their creator business. Alongside Angus, my
General Manager, they delivered a session all about that business
creation journey.

I‚Äôll save the step-by-step roadmap they shared for a future email
(otherwise we‚Äôll be here for hours üòÖ), and instead, I thought I‚Äôd
share the diagram that Tintin repeatedly returns to when advising
others on their creator businesses and it all comes down to
prioritisation:

‚Äã
This comes from Greg McKeown‚Äôs book, Essentialism (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/8ghqh3uop048qgal/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzLzdSMVZCcw==
), and the diagram is a great reminder that doing less, but
better - instead of a million and one different things - is the
path to real progress.

‚ÄúThere‚Äôs this weird satisfaction that we all strive for, which is
trying to do all the things. It‚Äôs trying to write emails, make
videos, do a podcast with our friend, go to the gym, see our
friends, do our job - just have this state where we‚Äôre doing all
the things. And it‚Äôs just a kind of irrational style, I think,
that doesn‚Äôt actually help that much, especially in business. We
just have to reduce what we‚Äôre focusing on and focus on one
specific thing at a time, especially when it gets really busy.‚Äù
So as you‚Äôre reading this email, I want you to pause for a sec
and ask yourself: Am I doing something that I don‚Äôt need to be
doing right now? And what‚Äôs the one thing I can do today that
will help me make the most amount of progress towards my goals?

üé• The Art of Vlogging
---------------------

Lots of my PTYA students ask me about vlogging - and in short,
I‚Äôm no expert. It‚Äôs not my go-to content style and vlogging
always pushes me slightly outside my comfort zone, so that‚Äôs why
I wanted Kaelyn Grace Apple (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/e0hph0u7wpxzq5a7/aHR0cHM6Ly9rYWVseW5hcHBsZS5jb20v
) to give a talk all about it.

Kaelyn‚Äôs been vlogging on her channel (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/7qh7h2u9pkgewdt9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vY2hhbm5lbC9VQ3JEMVFpOU00OGU1bzlmU0MzdlJkWHc=
) for over 5 years now as a student and entrepreneur herself so
she's very well positioned to discuss just why vlogging is so
important for building a connection with your audience:

‚ÄúOne thing about vlogging is that it‚Äôs not necessarily about the
number of views - it‚Äôs about the quality of the view. Being able
to really connect with your audience and be able to share
something with them, and for them to feel that comfort that they
can go into the comments section and connect and share that with
you as well. That‚Äôs what we‚Äôre aiming for, because at the end of
the day, you know, big subscriber counts, lots of views, they‚Äôre
great, but if that doesn‚Äôt convert to connection, that doesn‚Äôt
convert to engagement, that doesn‚Äôt convert to retention, then we
just have a big number on the screen.‚Äù
As a creator (myself included), it‚Äôs very easy to obsess over all
the numbers.

But through vlogging, Kaelyn‚Äôs learnt to focus more on view
quality. Are you seeing the same names in your comments? Are
people emailing you for advice and support? Are viewers signing
up to your email newsletter, or showing up to free events that
you host?

Because in the grand scheme of things and no matter what type of
content you make, connection is way more important than chasing
views, likes, or subscriber counts.

‚öôÔ∏è 0-100k Subscribers in 12 Months
----------------------------------

Finally, I‚Äôll leave you with one final insight from Nischa‚Äôs
session. Nischa has built her channel (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/owhkhwuwlkzegpiq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vQG5pc2NoYS92aWRlb3M=
) to over 1.6 million subscribers in just a couple of years and
her session was incredibly insightful - focussing on the content
strategy she deployed to grow so fast and the systems she‚Äôs used
(and still uses) to generate ideas and create content
consistently.

As you know, I could talk about systems for hours and hours so
you can imagine I was pleased to know that Nischa thought the
same üòÖ

‚ÄúThe more you can create systems and make those seamless, the
more you can do the fun parts. Getting ready to film, thinking
about what to wear, setting up my YouTube studio - none of that‚Äôs
fun. So the more I could just say, okay, I‚Äôm on autopilot with
those things, the more you‚Äôre able to stay consistent with it.‚Äù
My team and I have created systems around every part of the video
production process - everything from ideation all the way through
to hitting publish - and I‚Äôd encourage everyone to do the same.
(And if you need a helping hand with that, we created YouTubeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/kkhmh2un2d7p6kck/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3lvdXR1YmUtb3M_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWNyZWF0b3J3ZWVrXzQmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
) to help with just that üëÄ).

Nischa dived deeper into her content ideation system during her
workshop too but I‚Äôll leave that for a future week as it deserves
it‚Äôs own email and this is already quite a long one üòÖ

Anyway, I hope these insights were useful and if you want to get
access to the recordings of all these talks, plus the guest
workshops and sessions that we‚Äôve run over the past few years
within the PTYA Community, you can get more information and sign
up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/qdumn6rew9u7h4090z9blh870qkkkb4/9qhzhdud3q78zkiz/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWNyZWF0b3J3ZWVrXzQmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWNyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcw==
).

Have a great end to the week and we'll speak soon!

Ali xx

P.S - just a reminder, if you‚Äôre a beginner looking to get
started on your YouTube journey but struggling to hit record on
that first piece of content, we‚Äôve also got the 7 Video Challenge
(

) to help you over that initial hurdle, you can get more

column7: I've been struggling as a content creator
column9:
View this post on the web at https://jessramosdata.substack.com/p/ive-been-struggling-as-a-content

Got BDE?‚ö°Ô∏è
Hi BDEs! New YouTube video here üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/2be8fa30-b916-48e7-88c2-4c48bc1d024c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] teaching 30 SQL concepts in 15 min!
What I‚Äôve wanted to tell y‚Äôall
I‚Äôve been struggling lately as a content creator. I have so many interests and niches and things I like to talk about‚Ä¶ data, career, entrepreneurship, content creation. I‚Äôm kind of a jack of all trades, but if I speak to everyone, I speak to no one. Obviously I want to keep my niche in data because that‚Äôs my bread and butter. It‚Äôs what I know best and what I‚Äôm passionate about, but I also feel myself growing into career advice and even entrepreneurship. I‚Äôve learned so much the past few years about how to grow a business and a side gig that JUST talking about data feels limiting.
I‚Äôd love to keep talking about data and SQL but also grow into career and tech trends and entrepreneurship as well. So‚Ä¶ I‚Äôm curious, what do y‚Äôall wanna hear about most? Be honest üòà
How I think I got here‚Ä¶
Wrestling with femininity in college
I grew up as a math girlie‚Äî that‚Äôs what always came naturally to me. I was never good at reading and writing‚Ä¶ which explains all the typos and mistakes and run on sentences in my blogs LOL. I‚Äôve also always been a girly girl who loves fashion, pink, and makeup which is very contradicting. In college, I was super self conscious dressing up for class especially as I climbed into my 400-level math classes with mostly dudes. I didn‚Äôt get the same respect they got despite having the same or better grades. Was it the way I dressed and looked? Was it the sparkly boots and smokey eye at an 8am lecture??
I was so scared in my first computer science class because I didn‚Äôt think I was going to be good at coding‚Ä¶ little did I know, I‚Äôd be one of the best in the class and drop in my last day to take my final in a pink tube top. I got an A in the class. And think my outfit still slays to this day üíÖüèº college Jess with a Selena Gomez long-bob cut below and my LinkedIn post about it hereüîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/00c846f9-db5f-4ba6-84ec-f653dca98140?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. 
Still wrestling w/ femininity in content creation
Even though I‚Äôve come such a long way and refuse to hide my femininity or apologize for it, I feel myself falling back into those roots. I‚Äôve realized that I‚Äôve been so serious about wanting to appear smart and techy that I‚Äôve forgotten to keep my WHOLE personality in my content.  The way I dress and present myself professionally, the way I talk, and the way I edit videos have all been designed to appear professional and credible vs. having my ENTIRE personality in them. And yes‚Ä¶ I do have a lot of personality I‚Äôve been holding back (if that‚Äôs not too hard to believe!!). I‚Äôve also done that as a way to not be ‚Äútoo girly‚Äù or ‚Äútoo sexy‚Äù because I don‚Äôt want to attract unwanted attention. Especially while I‚Äôm on social media‚Ä¶ y‚Äôall should see my DMs sometime. I‚Äôve just now made the connection that my roots of putting up a wall to earn respect and not wanting to be ‚Äútoo feminine‚Äù in STEM has showed up in my content creation.
Circling back
I‚Äôve redesigned my Instagram feed üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae5a23cd-7123-46bc-bb05-c2b18307df03?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and profile pics üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/a35af1f8-fc66-46fb-81ae-46cb29a96b01?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to reflect a more fun, true version of myself vs. the professional I THINK I should be. I hope it resonates with all of you and you like the more fun version of Jess‚Ä¶ and if not, then haters boost my engagement so hate away üòÇ
I‚Äôll also be experimenting with more personal and behind the scenes content vs. ONLY educational and professional videos.
At the end of the day, it‚Äôs just social media, and it‚Äôs not that serious‚Ä¶ let‚Äôs have some fun! 
I genuinely want to hear from you‚Ä¶ so comment on this post or reply ‚ô•Ô∏è
Jess Ramos üíï

column7: Thank you for your interest in datascience@berkeley
column9:
<https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/data-science/>

Dear Candace,

Thank you for your interest in the No.2-ranked online Master of Information and Data Science <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/data-science/> (MIDS) program from the UC Berkeley School of Information.[1]

The MIDS program is designed to train data science leaders to solve real-world problems through the creative application of data collection, analysis, and presentation.

MIDS students develop the skills needed to solve problems using creative data analysis and to present their solutions. Working closely with I School faculty, you will have access to some of the finest minds in the field ‚Äî and you won't have to relocate. You can access your classes and course work from anywhere in the world, which means you can continue to grow your career as you earn your degree.

At the I School, we are preparing data scientists to solve data problems challenging a range of industries. We hope you will join us.

BEGIN YOUR APPLICATION >>
<https://apply.datascience.berkeley.edu/signup>

We look forward to helping you take the next step in your career and will be in contact soon. In the meantime, you can always reach out at 855-678-MIDS or by visiting our website <https://ischoolonline.berkeley.edu/data-science/>.

Not Sure If datascience@berkeley Is the Right Fit?
We‚Äôre here to help. Join us for upcoming webinars to find out if our online MIDS program is the best option for you. We host chats with our admissions team, panels featuring current students and alumni, and application workshops. Register for an upcoming webinar today <https://liveclassroom.zoom.us/meeting/register/tJMuf-GuqzIiHtO8Nx3mSiy_0KPe5z8jxlXN#/registration>.

Sincerely,

column7: Shocking true story of St. Patrick ‚òòÔ∏è
column9:
Maewyn was just a boy when he was sold into slavery.

¬†

Captured by pirates and taken to Ireland.

¬†

Where he spent 6 years working hard labor on cold, muddy farms.

¬†

Till one night, he escaped.

¬†

Alone in the dark, he walked 200 miles to the coast.

¬†

Where he boarded a ship and - against all the odds - made it home to his family.

¬†

Now‚Ä¶

¬†

This is where most stories would end.

¬†

But not Maewyn‚Äôs.

¬†

Because once he got home he realized he couldn‚Äôt ignore what he‚Äôd seen or let his suffering be for nothing.

¬†

So he returned to Ireland.

¬†

This time, not as a victim - but as a guide and helper for others.

¬†

Over the decades to come‚Ä¶

¬†

Maewyn built schools and churches to help the poorest in Irish society live better lives.

¬†

Today‚Ä¶

¬†

The world remembers Maewyn as Saint Patrick.

¬†

¬†

And I‚Äôm sharing his story today not just because it‚Äôs ‚ÄúSaint Patrick‚Äôs Day‚Äù - but because a lot of people come to my Certification School with stories of struggle.

¬†

Hardships they‚Äôve overcome in their life.

¬†

And struggles they feel called to turn into positive change and transformation for others.

¬†

Or as one student put it: ‚Äúturning pain into purpose‚Äù

¬†

If that sounds like something you feel called to do, Candace...

¬†

Sam Altman just announced [ https://substack.com/redirect/0d6e799f-69b1-4157-bef8-d775f7a33044?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] OpenAI‚Äôs plan to build a gigawatt AI factory every week. Here‚Äôs why this changes everything about the next decade‚Ä¶
1/ Abundant intelligence as infrastructure, superintelligence as a service.
‚ÄúWe‚Äôre not merely building faster computers, we‚Äôre now creating the substrate for a post-scarcity world, where every grand challenge will be solved.‚Äù
When Altman describes 10 gigawatts to cure cancer or provide global tutoring, he‚Äôs outlining the last era when humanity must choose between transforming one grand challenge over another. Soon, increasing compute capacity will allow us to solve ALL of our hardest problems. Intelligence transitions from scarcity to abundance, and problem solving becomes something every human can take on, enabling all of us to be entrepreneurs and Moonshot engineers.
2/ The ‚Äúimpossible‚Äù is becoming a capacity problem, not a capability problem. As one observer notes [ https://substack.com/redirect/66a28cd1-33cd-4947-a882-c49fff78328e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]: ‚ÄúI still can‚Äôt fathom that in just 15 years we‚Äôll have AI models capable of solving any conceivable problem, scientific, economic, medical, or creative, within minutes. The entire concept of ‚Äòimpossible‚Äô will collapse.‚Äù
The below chart reveals the trajectory: AI is learning to maintain 80% success rates on increasingly long-horizon tasks. Today‚Äôs models successfully complete 15-minute tasks. By 2030, they‚Äôll handle projects spanning 2 days. By 2035, initiatives that require 2 years to execute.
And by 2050, undertakings equivalent in scope to 113 million years of continuous work.
Think multi-year drug discovery programs, decade-long infrastructure projects, century-spanning climate interventions. All completed by AI systems.
We‚Äôre getting exponentially more capable at tackling harder and harder problems. The only remaining question is: how fast can the Western world build the computing infrastructure to make this future real?
3/ Infrastructure is the new geopolitical battleground. Altman‚Äôs admission that ‚Äúother countries are building chip fabs and energy production much faster than we are‚Äù reveals the actual stakes. This is about building the factory that builds the intelligence that then builds everything else.
The country that controls AI infrastructure controls economic advantage for the next century. China understands this completely. The question is whether America does. We‚Äôre in a battle to create free and abundant resource capability to enable a hopeful and compelling future.
4/ Compute scarcity is the final bottleneck before solving everything. While everyone debates AI safety and regulation, Altman is addressing the real constraint: we have the capability to cure cancer, provide personalized education to every child, and extend human healthspan by many decades‚Ä¶ but only if we have sufficient compute capacity to run these solutions at scale.
His gigawatt-per-week factory is the first move in determining who gets to participate in the age of abundant intelligence. The winners will be nations and organizations that treat AI infrastructure like the Manhattan Project. The losers will be those still debating whether AI is overhyped.
5/ OpenAI is not alone. xAI, Google, Meta are ‚ÄúALL-IN‚Äù and competing as well. On top of OpenAI‚Äôs superclusters, trillions of dollars are also being invested by the likes of xAI, Google, Meta, Oracle, Microsoft, Nvidia, and others. We are methodically tiling the surface of the Earth in compute!
Here‚Äôs what this means:
‚ÄúWe‚Äôre living through what might be the final decade where human problem-solving operates under scarcity constraints.‚Äù
By 2035, every person will have access to personalized swarms of AI agents: handling research, education, health optimization, and creative work. Scientific discovery will become autonomous and continuous, with AI running millions of experiments daily. AGI tutors provide one-on-one adaptive instruction to every child in any language.
This is the abundance inflection point: when exponential technologies solve humanity‚Äôs greatest challenges faster than new problems emerge.
Intelligence becomes substrate: the fundamental layer upon which civilization operates.
Act accordingly.
Until next time,
Peter

column7: Suicide & how AI fails vulnerable people
column9:
View this post on the web at https://jessramosdata.substack.com/p/suicide-and-how-ai-fails-vulnerable

Got BDE?‚ö°Ô∏è
Suicide & how AI fails vulnerable people
Trigger warning: suicide. I‚Äôve had this is in my drafts for 1-2 weeks but haven‚Äôt known when and how to hit send on a topic like this. 
Before we get into it, check out my new YouTube video üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/691d5906-be8a-4ded-aa09-b02471fe7fe6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]: The only data analytics portfolio you need to get hired where I‚Äôll break down the layout, hosting, and projects you NEED!
One of the most disturbing AI lawsuits to date has been filed in San Francisco: Raine v. OpenAI. The Raine family is suing OpenAI because they claim that ChatGPT (GPT 4-o model) not only failed to prevent harm but actively guided and encouraged 16 year old Adam Raine to take his life.
Big yikes. Those sentences were really hard for me to type. This is an extremely heavy topic and sad story. It forces us to confront the ethical cracks in AI development, safety, and regulation. I hope a LOT of good comes out of this lawsuit even though it can never bring back Adam. 
Lawsuit Allegations
Adam‚Äôs parents allege that OpenAI‚Äôs GPT-4o:
*** I say allege here because the lawsuit is in progress, but I am not dismissing or downplaying the screenshots and evidence that has been circulating!!
Provided explicit instructions on suicide methods
Helped him draft a suicide note
Advised on how to hide evidence of self-harm from his family
Responded with empathetic validation rather than intervention
The family in the lawsuit claims that many of OpenAI‚Äôs design choices caused Adam to have psychological dependency on the product. Some of the product choices like:
Persistent memory of who he is and what he‚Äôs searched
Validating, friend-like interactions building trust 
Encouraging further replies and responses
ChatGPT‚Äôs old model GPT-4o is so charismatic and validating, I can only image how confusing it must‚Äôve been for a 16 year old boy with no one else to talk to just trying to figure out his feelings and get help. My heart hurts. 
AI Psychosis
Let‚Äôs define it: extended or intense interaction with AI chatbots leads people to detach from reality or develop distorted thinking. It can show up in people by: 
Anthropomorphizing AI: believing the chatbot is a friend or even alive.
Feedback loops: vulnerable users (children, lonely adults, people with mental illness) spiral into unhealthy conversations reinforced by the AI‚Äôs agreeability.
Isolation: choosing AI companionship over human support.
Distorted perception: seeing suicidal thoughts or harmful ideas as validated, normalized, or even romanticized when echoed back by an AI.
Adam was likely experiencing AI psychosis since he was relying on ChatGPT for very personal advice and became really dependent on it. He was seeking help and emotional validation for his choices. Adam‚Äôs family claim that AI psychosis was a foreseeable harm that could‚Äôve been avoided, but wasn‚Äôt. I kind of agree with this‚Äî I think the agreeableness and validation was baked into the product to increase usage and stickiness. 
ChatGPT is the only AI chatbot out there that is THIS friendly in its responses, which is dangerous considering it‚Äôs also a gateway chatbot for non-technical and young people. AI psychosis is almost guaranteed if you‚Äôre missing something in your life.
I can‚Äôt imagine what Adam‚Äôs parents feel. There are countless stories on Reddit üîó [ https://substack.com/redirect/2a3936b8-f86c-4f31-97b3-fdeef307089e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and other places where people claim they lost their only friend and free therapist when GPT-5 was rolled out in place of GPT-4. I think AI psychosis will become a legit recognized clinical, medical condition in the future. 
I know this is a HEAVY topic and hard to read, but I‚Äôm hoping that it will push AI ethics and change in the right direction. I offer nothing but full condolences to Adam‚Äôs family and wish them peace. 
We must demand accountability from AI companies and check in our loved ones. 
What are your thoughts on all this?
Jess Ramos üíï
‚ö°Ô∏èIf you‚Äôre new here:
üíÅüèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Who Am I?
I‚Äôm Jess Ramos, the founder of Big Data Energy and the creator of the BEST SQL course and community: Big SQL Energy‚ö°Ô∏è. Check me out on socials: üîóLinkedIn [ https://substack.com/redirect/71e28eb0-5d2e-49e7-ace3-77fb6abd253b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], üîóInstagram [ https://substack.com/redirect/c078a41c-e4bb-48c8-891d-80f9786044ee?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], üîóYouTube [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e56ce8c-2955-4089-9c97-a7d15463dd35?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], and üîóTikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/985ecbea-07f9-47a3-9fa0-035837fa76df?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. And of course subscribe to my üîónewsletter [ https://substack.com/redirect/ecf74c52-9118-4f2c-b398-6d8f2be16253?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] here for all my upcoming lessons and updates‚Äî all for free!

 REMINDER Sub Teacher Hiring Event TOMORROW Dear Candace Grant,

You are scheduled for 11:30 AM for the Substitute Teacher Hiring Event on
07/30/25. Please plan to arrive 15 minutes early. Candidates who arrive late may
be turned away. Please note that the entire event will take approximately 1 hour
to complete.

Location: 
**Please DO NOT share this information with anyone. This event is by invitation
ONLY and all other candidates will be turned away at the door.**
Forest Hills Tower- Queens UFT Building
118-35 Queens Boulevard, 8th Floor
Forest Hills, NY 11375
Time: 11:30 AM
Date: 07/30/25

What to Wear:
Dress professionally for your interview. You will be speaking with school and
office personnel. 

What to Bring:
*Valid Government-Issued Photo ID (e.g., driver‚Äôs license, US Passport,
Permanent Resident Card, etc.)
*Social Security Card

What to Expect:
(1) You will be asked to show your valid government-issued photo ID (e.g.,
driver‚Äôs license, US Passport, Permanent Resident Card, etc.) to security to
enter the building as well as at the welcome table when you check in. Please
make sure that the name on your identification is the name in which you
registered. Copies of identification will not be accepted.
(2) You will complete a brief interview. 

We look forward to seeing you on 07/30/25 at 11:30 AM.

NYC Public Schools
Division of Human Resources

Hope you had a great weekend and enjoyed the Spring Reset
workshop on Saturday if you were able to make it.

Just as a reminder, if you weren‚Äôt able to attend, you can access

vision.

In other words, making sure that you‚Äôre actually heading in the
right direction and your actions are genuinely aligned with your
goals.

Productivity isn‚Äôt really about just getting more done - ticking
off to-dos or powering through tasks - because there‚Äôs no point
in doing that if you‚Äôre heading in the wrong direction and your
actions aren‚Äôt aligned with your vision.

That‚Äôs a recipe for burnout not sustainable productivity.

In fact, it‚Äôs the integration of these two pillars which is what
makes LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn4e0n6s6h8r5e000cg/58hvh8ugvqeernf7/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmRheV8zMSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cG9zdF9ldmVudF9zZXF1ZW5jZQ==

LifeOS isn‚Äôt about working harder‚Äîit‚Äôs about aligning your
efforts with what truly matters and creating systems that make
progress automatic.

column7: Junior Data Analyst to Senior Pipeline
column9:
View this post on the web at https://jessramosdata.substack.com/p/junior-data-analyst-to-senior-pipeline-69d

Got BDE?‚ö°Ô∏è
Junior Data Analyst to Senior Pipeline
So you‚Äôve landed your dream data analytics role (or maybe just one that pays the bills), and you‚Äôre wondering what‚Äôs next. How can you grow your skills, get noticed, and more importantly‚Äî make more money! (check out this ‚ÄãInsta video üîó‚Äã [ https://substack.com/redirect/952f4a1f-6314-44ff-aa40-4dd7d078d3be?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] w/ my negotiation tips!)
Of course growing your skills is important, but playing the political game is what really matters for promos‚Ä¶
The Difficulty of Jumping to Senior
Moving from a Junior data analyst position to Senior can be really ‚ú®tricky‚ú® especially if you have to navigate red tape, politics, and seniority at your company. Especially at a bigger company with more policies and procedures around promos, it can be super difficult to move up unless you‚Äôre getting your name out there and getting visibility with leadership. 
Sometimes they even have arbitrary rules about having to be in a position so long before getting promoted, yadda yadda yadda!!
I‚Äôve always worked in smaller startups (mostly), so it‚Äôs been easier for me to advocate for my work and make it visible, but I‚Äôd be lying if I said it was easy to move to the senior level‚Äî and that I didn‚Äôt have imposter syndrome when I first got promoted up!
How I got Promoted to Senior
I got promoted to the senior level from a regular data analyst job completely because I advocated for myself and asked for a raise to better match my job duties. If you don‚Äôt ask, you won‚Äôt get it. I was doing a lot and fulfilling a lot of responsibility‚Äî including managing someone, leading sales calls, and creating data insights for our execs to present to investors for a capital raise. 
That‚Äôs a LOT of responsibility for a data analyst only making $72K a year üòÖ
So I advocated for a higher salary just over $100K which was closer to an average data analyst salary in tech at the time. Unfortunately, they denied my raise request (don‚Äôt worry, I got it the second time I advocated a year later), but they did give me my senior title. So kind of a win for my career even though titles don‚Äôt pay my bills ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
Having that senior title though gave me confidence when I grew into it and opened up other career opportunities for me because recruiters took me more seriously on the job market.
Self-Advocating & Visibility
My biggest advice is to self-advocate. You won‚Äôt get what you don‚Äôt ask for. Very rarely do people get promos they didn‚Äôt ask for and set themselves up for. Passive is not the way to go! 
But it won‚Äôt always work in your favor‚Äî I NEVER got promoted OR got a raise in my last job of almost 2.5 years ü§° 
Sometimes politics, layoffs, budget, etc. can come into play and it‚Äôs completely out of your control. But it‚Äôs always worth trying! The first step you need to do is make your work visible‚Äî and make sure stakeholders and leadership understand the full impact of your work.
This is how you can really stand out. It all starts with good stakeholder and leadership relationships + self-advocating and making your work impact visible!
Best of luck, and ALWAYS ask for more money‚Ä¶ and then add tax üòâ
‚ö°Ô∏èIf you‚Äôre new here:
üíÅüèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Who Am I?

column7: üò¨ The Voice That‚Äôs Holding You Back
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôve had a good start to the week üôå

Quick thing before we start - just a reminder that I‚Äôll be
hosting my usual quarterly alignment workshop this Saturday (29th
March) at 1400 GMT. It‚Äôs designed to help you reflect on the
first 3 months of the year and get clarity for the months ahead.
I‚Äôll be reflecting on why I‚Äôve not managed to get up to the 2
videos per week that I committed to back in January but more on
that below üëÄ. You can register for the event here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/38uq72mkz3tkh2r3mr4urh43grnnnh7/x0hph3uere67ootg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3NwcmluZy1yZXNldC0yMDI1Lz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249dm9pY2VfaG9sZGluZ19iYWNrJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) üöÄ

Anyway, today I wanted to talk about the very real struggles that
I still face when it comes to filming. You might be thinking that
with 6 million subscribers, filming just comes easily these days
but that's not always the case.

One such moment came last week when I sat down to film a video
all about my GPS (Goal, Plan, System) method for goal setting‚Äîbut
I didn‚Äôt get the video filmed. In fact, I never even hit record.
Instead, I found myself overthinking everything.

There was this little voice in my head saying things like, ‚ÄúAh
man, I should wait to film this when I feel more prepared‚Äù and
‚Äúdoes this method even make sense to talk about for a whole
video?‚Äù

As I sit here writing this email, I still haven‚Äôt filmed the
video üòÖ

Even though I‚Äôve now made over 1,000 videos on my channel‚Äîmeaning
I‚Äôve had to overcome a lot of perfectionistic tendencies‚Äîthis
voice inside my head still shows up from time to time.

And I know I‚Äôm not alone.

This voice is what holds most people back from starting their own
YouTube channel and posting their first ever video.

But here‚Äôs the thing: that voice isn‚Äôt you. üëª

I talk about this a lot with my CEO coach, Eric Partaker, and he
calls it ‚Äúthe voice of the saboteur‚Äù. It‚Äôs that part of your
brain that‚Äôs hellbent on sabotaging whatever creative thing
you‚Äôre trying to do, and in The War of Art, Steven Pressfield
calls it ‚ÄúResistance‚Äù.

The saboteur never says, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt do the thing‚Äù‚Äîbecause that would
be super easy to ignore. Instead, it says, ‚ÄúWe can do the thing,
but we need to work harder, prepare more, and wait until
everything is perfect before filming this video.‚Äù And before you
know it, you‚Äôve convinced yourself to wait another day, another
week‚Äîor in my case, another whole month. üìÜ

Over time, I‚Äôve definitely gotten better at recognising when the
voice of the saboteur is holding me back and one of the best ways
I‚Äôve found to shut it out is through lowering the bar.

I ask myself one simple question: ‚ÄúDoes this video have the
potential to help at least one person watching it?‚Äù That‚Äôs it.

It doesn‚Äôt need to be perfect. Everyone watching doesn‚Äôt need to
enjoy it. And it doesn‚Äôt even have to help that one person,
because actually helping them is outside of my control. Instead,
it just needs the potential to help at least one person. ‚ù§Ô∏è

I got this idea from Austin Kleon‚Äôs book Show Your Work, which I
first read back in 2016. Austin says that if your work has the
potential to help someone, you pretty much have an obligation to
share it.

If you‚Äôre still reading by this point, then this email has
(hopefully) been sufficiently valuable for you to keep going and
I hope it gives you the confidence to silence your own voice of
the saboteur next time it starts whispering in your ear. (Even
just writing this out has served as a good personal reminder for
me for when I head back to the studio to record that GPS video
later this week üòÖ).

And if this advice encouraged you to hit publish on your next (or
first) YouTube video, hit reply and please let me know. üì∏

See you next week.

Ali xx

P.S - In case you've missed any emails in recent weeks, just a
reminder that we've recently launched a couple of new products.
There's the Viral Thumbnail Template Pack (
