column7: Important updates to your Pro account usage limits
column9:
Hi there,



Next month, we're introducing new weekly rate limits for Claude subscribers, 
affecting less than 5% of users based on current usage patterns.



Claude Code, especially as part of our subscription bundle, has seen 
unprecedented growth. At the same time, we‚Äôve identified policy violations like 
account sharing and reselling access‚Äîand advanced usage patterns like running 
Claude 24/7 in the background‚Äîthat are impacting system capacity for all. Our 
new rate limits address these issues and provide a more equitable experience 
for all users.



What‚Äôs changing:

Starting August 28, we're introducing weekly usage limits alongside our 
existing 5-hour limits:

 * Current: Usage limit that resets every 5 hours (no change)
 * New: Overall weekly limit that resets every 7 days
 * New: Claude Opus 4 weekly limit that resets every 7 days
 * As we learn more about how developers use Claude Code, we may adjust usage 
limits to better serve our community.


What this means for you:

 * Most users won't notice any difference. The weekly limits are designed to 
support typical daily use across your projects.
 * Most Pro users can expect 40-80 hours of Sonnet 4 within their weekly rate 
limits. This will vary based on factors such as codebase size and user settings 
like auto-accept mode. Users running multiple Claude Code instances in parallel 
will hit their limits sooner.
 * You can manage or cancel your subscription anytime in Settings 
<https://claude.ai/settings/billing>.
We take these decisions seriously. We're committed to supporting long-running 
use cases through other options in the future, but until then, weekly limits 
will help us maintain reliable service for everyone.



We also recognize that during this same period, users have encountered several 
reliability and performance issues. We've been working to fix these as quickly 
as possible, and will continue addressing any remaining issues over the coming 
days and weeks.



‚ÄìThe Anthropic Team




 <https://www.anthropic.com/?utm_source=email>

 <https://x.com/anthropicai> 
<https://www.linkedin.com/company/anthropicresearch> 
<https://www.youtube.com/@anthropic-ai>

September 3, 2025

Design‚Äôs moral grey zone: Navigating client ethics in 2025
Design‚Äôs moral grey zone:

Navigating client ethics in

2025

‚Ää
Today, every click and every client carries an unspoken ethical weight and designers are facing increasingly complex questions about the impact of their work. From rejecting fossil fuel contracts to reconsidering UX dark patterns, the question isn‚Äôt just what you design, it‚Äôs who you‚Äôre designing for. Elizabeth Goodspeed speaks with creatives from Pentagram, Koto, Creech, and beyond to unpack what it means to stay true to your values without sacrificing your career in today‚Äôs competitive design world.

Also in this issue
* How BOFF Coffee fuses street life, spatial design, and neighborhood culture
* SuperSonic Kiupai blends Colombian cool with mayo-inspired kawaii nostalgia
* üì£ ONE MORE MONTH to get 90% off Freshbooks for 4 months with Dribbble Pro

‚Ää

Can designers ever truly choose who they work for?

Is it possible to stay ethical in design without going broke or burning out? That‚Äôs the problem Elizabeth Goodspeed explores in this feature, where designers from studios like Pentagram, Koto, and Creech reflect on where (and how) they draw their ethical lines. They discuss everything from refusing projects tied to alcohol or fossil fuels to the slippery ethics of UX dark patterns re: accessibility. Designers share stories of uncomfortable compromises, selective portfolios, and the quiet power of saying no.

Some studios use the UN‚Äôs Sustainable Development Goals as a compass; others rely on personal lived experience and gut checks to guide client decisions. But privilege, power dynamics, and economics always complicate things. This article ultimately challenges designers to think critically about the world their work supports, urging them to pay attention, draw boundaries where they can, and reject the common theme that just because we can‚Äôt be perfect, our choices don‚Äôt matter.

column7: üëÄ¬†An Insight into our A/B Testing Strategy
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope you‚Äôre having a great week so far üôå

First off, huge shoutout to everyone who attended our final
quarterly reset workshop of the year last Saturday. It was
amazing to see so many of you taking the time to properly reflect
on the past 90 days (including celebrating some fantastic YouTube
wins) and set intentions for finishing 2025 strong.

Speaking of YouTube wins, the ‚ÄúHow To Change Your Life‚Äù video (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wxqq2tvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/x0hph3uew6w2ombg/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dD0ycyZ2PWdPMGJ2VF9zbWRN
) I mentioned last week where I talk about this idea of a Think
Day is continuing to perform really well, and I thought it would
be interesting to double down on one of the key things that
helped this video succeed.

Now, there‚Äôs always an element of luck with YouTube video
performance (unfortunately üòÖ), but there are certain things you
can do to dramatically increase the chances of a video doing
well, like optimising your title and thumbnail, nailing a decent
hook, and all that good stuff that we talk about in PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wxqq2tvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/6qhehoul7g7rzqb9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWFiXzI0JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) and these emails.

But one of the things I haven‚Äôt spoken much about is A/B testing,
which is a powerful tool that every creator can use no how matter
big or small your channel, and we do a lot of this behind the
scenes (thanks to Becky, my YouTube Producer üôè)

The first golden rule is that we always test one variable at a
time. Why? Because if you change both the thumbnail and title
simultaneously, you‚Äôll have no idea which one actually made the
difference and you won‚Äôt be able to correctly attribute what‚Äôs
contributing to a higher watch-time share and click-through rate.

Regarding our actual process for A/B testing, we always start
with the most ‚Äúmacro‚Äù change - meaning we choose to test either
two very different thumbnails OR two very different titles. Never
both at once.

Then, based on the winner, we funnel into progressively smaller,
more micro changes, and I‚Äôll show you exactly how we did this for
the think day vlog.

Test 1Ô∏è‚É£ - Macro thumbnail variations

During the first A/B test, we compared two different thumbnail
concepts and it was clear very soon after publishing that the
second thumbnail was a definite winner.

(You‚Äôre typically looking for a 10%+ difference between the two
options - anything less than that and you might want to keep
testing for a bit longer.)

‚Äã
Test 2Ô∏è‚É£ - Micro title variations

Once we had this winning thumbnail locked in, we then tested two
slightly different titles and the shorter one was preferred
(albeit the difference is much smaller this time).

‚Äã
We haven‚Äôt yet done any further tests, and of course, this could
be an infinite process. But typically, a third test would involve
more subtle variations, like different thumbnail text, colours,
or background elements.

I find this whole A/B testing stuff pretty fascinating because
even seemingly small changes to the way you package a video can
make a surprisingly big difference to how it performs.

Having said that, one thing I will caution about A/B testing is
that you don‚Äôt want to overdo it. Running too many tests without
waiting to get meaningful data can actually be more harmful than
helpful to your video performance.

In particular, if a video is performing really well in the first
12-24 hours, it might just be better to hold off on A/B testing
for a bit. Why? Because introducing a weaker variant could
actually pull down your overall performance and limit how much
the algorithm promotes your video.

If you have any other questions, feel free to hit reply and I can
always talk about A/B testing again in a future email if a lot of
you have similar concerns.

And if you‚Äôre already creating content on YouTube, I‚Äôd love to
hear about the A/B tests you‚Äôve been experimenting with to grow
your channel - feel free to hit reply and let me know.

Speak soon,

Ali xx

P.S. To all the beginners out there, the most important thing to
focus on at first is making great content. No amount of A/B
testing can save a video that people don‚Äôt want to watch, so if
you‚Äôre keen to learn exactly how to get started on YouTube then
I‚Äôd love for you to join PTYA. Click here to check it out (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wxqq2tvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/6qhehoul7g7rzqb9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYWxpYWJkYWFsLmNvbS9wYXJ0LXRpbWUteW91dHViZXItYWNhZGVteS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWFiXzI0JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) üëÄ

üõ£Ô∏è Not another workflow builder

One of the most common requests we've received since day one has been for a visual workflow builder. Our CEO Harrison explains why we haven't built one, and why we believe the next problem to solve is creating reliably good agents in a no-code way with agents. üîê Agent Auth

column7: The Gigawatt Wars: US Losing to China
column9:
View this post on the web at https://metatrends.substack.com/p/the-gigawatt-wars-us-losing-to-china

The AI race isn‚Äôt about algorithms, models, or talent; it‚Äôs about energy. And right now, China is winning.
1/ The AI race is the energy race. The first nation (or organization) to achieve sustainable energy will unlock the GPUs required to reach AGI. AI‚Äôs energy appetite is about to explode. By 2030, global data center capacity demand [ https://substack.com/redirect/a003021d-a89f-4fc3-9d42-4f55a70f7b2c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] will nearly triple to 219 gigawatts, with 70% driven by AI workloads. The capital required is $6.7 trillion worldwide for data center infrastructure, and $5.2 trillion for AI workloads alone.
Whoever controls energy infrastructure at scale controls the economic advantage for the next century. This is our generation‚Äôs infrastructure moment.
2/ China is winning the energy race while the US continues to lag. In 2024, China installed 329 GW of solar capacity [ https://substack.com/redirect/da6034a5-5215-42b6-bfee-dd8f630cdf2c?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]: six times more than the United States. Not double. Not triple. Six times. While we installed 50 GW, they installed enough clean energy to power six UKs.
Between 2025 and 2029, China is projected to add 2 TW of new solar capacity. Meanwhile, US solar installations are expected to decline 8% in 2026, dropping from 51 GW to 47 GW as policy uncertainty freezes investor confidence.
Here‚Äôs what this means: China captured 76% of global clean-tech factory investment in 2024. While America debates regulations, China is methodically tiling the Earth in solar panels and battery production. They‚Äôre not merely winning the energy race‚Ä¶ they‚Äôre lapping us.
3/ Clean energy isn‚Äôt optional anymore‚Äîit‚Äôs the substrate layer for everything that comes next. BloombergNEF reports [ https://substack.com/redirect/c248e4b1-67b5-4a51-b962-6cf096e8ecc0?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] that US renewable investment fell 36% in the first half of 2025, while China maintained its 44% share of global clean energy investment. The EU saw investment jump 63% as capital fled American policy uncertainty.
Asia-Pacific including China will maintain 70% of global solar market share through 2029. India is racing ahead, projected to overtake the US for second place in solar installations with 237 GW expected versus our 218 GW. The winners of the AI race will be the regions that solved the energy equation first.
This isn‚Äôt about environmentalism. This is about whether American companies have access to the abundant, cheap, clean energy required to power the gigawatt AI factories that will cure cancer, extend healthspan, provide personalized education to every child, and solve our hardest problems.
Here‚Äôs the opportunity: we have the technology, the capital, and the innovation ecosystem to win this race.
The next wave‚Äîfusion, advanced SMRs, next-generation geothermal‚Äîis coming online this decade. Solar, wind, and storage are proven technologies today. By 2035, we‚Äôll see hyper-efficient perovskite solar cells hitting 30%+ efficiency, AI-optimized microgrids balancing energy loads autonomously, and upgraded infrastructure replacing fossil fuel plants with clean baseload power.
The path to abundant intelligence runs directly through abundant energy. If we prioritize upgrading our energy infrastructure now‚Äîwith the same urgency we‚Äôre applying to AI development‚Äîwe unlock the compute capacity needed to power the transformation Sam Altman recently outlined [ https://substack.com/redirect/b05c4041-27cc-4ffc-9f26-033bd4031aae?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]: solving every grand challenge, making the impossible merely a capacity problem.
The winners will be nations that move fast. Not those who debate whether to move. The technology exists. The capital is available. The question is velocity.
This is America‚Äôs moment to lead the most important infrastructure build in history. The race isn‚Äôt over. It‚Äôs just beginning‚Ä¶
Until next time,
Peter
PS‚ÄîWorth Your Attention
In just a few days, I‚Äôll be hosting one of my favorite conversations‚Äîlive, onstage, in front of our exclusive XPRIZE Visioneering 2025 [ https://substack.com/redirect/dad63ff8-729e-46d4-aa93-ea8b7cbbc601?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] audience with some of my Moonshot Mates.
Join us [ https://substack.com/redirect/dad63ff8-729e-46d4-aa93-ea8b7cbbc601?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] October 23‚Äì25, 2025, there are only a few seats left and registration closes at 10am PT on Monday, October 20th.
PPS‚ÄîCheck This Out
There is a group organizing community dinners for Moonshot podcast listeners in Los Angeles. If you are in Los Angeles and want to spend some time with fellow listeners, you can sign up here: moonshotdinners.com [ https://substack.com/redirect/d1f8058f-cc9a-48b3-aa32-a069ff33d3bf?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].

Hey Candace,

I just heard one of my students talking about how, before they joined my school, they thought coaching = mentoring.

¬†

But they‚Äôre actually very different.

¬†

Winston, one of my students from Ontario, Canada, found this out when he joined my school last year.

¬†

He‚Äôd built a lifetime of experience and knowledge in high-level and senior corporate roles.

¬†

And now he felt called to share with others in a more meaningful way.

¬†

He thought that meant coaching.

¬†

But what he discovered inside my coaching Certification School ( https://pages.jayshettycoaching.com/ovsl-video-bau-e/?el=OVSL-email-coaching-162-2&utm_campaign_name=JSCS%3A+Prospects+Week+162-2&utm_content_name=coaching+%E2%89%A0+mentoring&utm_medium_name=email_action&utm_source_name=customer.io ) flipped his idea of coaching on its head.

¬†

You see‚Ä¶

¬†

‚ùå Winston discovered that life coaching is NOT about teaching.

¬†

‚úÖ It‚Äôs about empowering others to find answers within themselves - not telling them how to live their life.

¬†

Before joining my school, he had no idea coaching could be used this way.

¬†

That it was NOT about how smart or successful you are.

¬†

But how well you apply specific life coaching techniques that help others open doors within themselves.

This perspective shift alongside his new life coaching skills helped Winston serve his clients in a profound new way.

¬†

And also helped him serve himself - through self-reflection and self-auditing.

¬†

If you want to find out if you have what it takes to coach like this‚Ä¶

[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/au60ERwl8bvAzaIBDSZR-A~~/AAAAARA~/BuHc0jQb9cWu6cW9xlifGdATEIsWwM2DAqL3XXR8ktrAVVAuWFYYKyUuK56KE6axxSIX8V27YBFdu3KSIX_GU01Bs_xeA5CBkZPBWs9DtN7MCqq_UvRHDSDEbpB-9glhVRQCMiX7-xXc_0J5lPxGTs1-WQFNHJQqU5EI7NWh39t2cFTM4jWrTVpbBAMvzqTap5xe2zp2Ntmqv1dqHBl9ZWb7PBiBgTy4eGGa2ZXUn1ytF607DKzsKeUGpttwK2Ks3zVifCUUg1MzyGsBvVFxV010hkAgdyLtWMQz4QPNbpY9o3Tx2oraiT1DV9CYlRfDSlv5GmaABkgy6UqXftPfow~~]

I‚Äôm the editor of this newsletter.

Every few years, I get a little thrill when I receive my jury summons. Most
people hate this hassle, but I like the idea of making my small civic
contribution. I pack a book, call out of work and head to the courthouse. Yet
I‚Äôve never been selected. I guess it‚Äôs nice to get my day back, but it leaves me
a little forlorn. (Trial lawyers tell me they often avoid seating journalists
because we‚Äôre more likely to know things about high-profile cases. Also, when
you‚Äôre trained to seek more information, it‚Äôs tough to consider only what you‚Äôre
told in court.)

But I felt less wistful about my exclusion after I read a story The Times
published today. It‚Äôs about what happens to jurors in trials for the most
disturbing crimes
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/qbmd4H6-Th0-B9hyt6auSA~~/AAAAARA~/hzq_9VqRnWLrtLxVop6fRfjr16A8ZQiC1KH57I4XaiVhHUlZmE2v-bZLYDC7bwIk0i5BaOdv_78iO5JhymW8BsaQuKxZ2yOHFdXa403crv3-MhZplTXLq6rcR2FI4mfSZbfSxtYmZaX0CIoVEMaU5ILxSPbpxazPCdMRLIsYzyP7qqujBr4wozLROxTIhz18Adl4d7rSpDbZARo5AUbeml7BQ6psd-tnki9E0supMWRa4BhyaKVfIMFji0rWsU61WGMnyyTzIyp9Yur9USh9iomhHCf-wePxPTjeTYW4eVqQgpTlZg5R7OpTDXXOoSFN_g5q88cNB3GXc7y2_ysmAUu6c9rPWCxznrpODkSy7xSqFoZYSBn6hdB_JYzwtLZK]
. They might spend weeks contemplating gruesome acts and examining
spine-chilling evidence. But they‚Äôre forbidden to discuss any of it. Carrying
around these dark thoughts, the science says, may lead to years of trauma. I
asked Liz Krieger, the freelance reporter who wrote the piece, about the issue.

Did you get the idea for this story from your own jury service? What happened?

I was selected for a child sexual abuse case in Brooklyn last November. For
seven days, I examined graphic photographic evidence and listened to testimony
about abuse of a baby. The judge‚Äôs instructions were clear: We couldn‚Äôt talk
about the trial with anyone ‚Äî not our spouses, friends or even fellow jurors. I
found myself replaying these horrific images with no outlet to process them. I‚Äôd
go home to make dinner for my own kids, haunted by what I‚Äôd seen. It felt like
being forced to swallow poison and then being told not to seek an antidote.

And you realized you couldn‚Äôt be the only person struggling in this way.

Exactly. More than a million Americans serve on juries each year, and half of
those cases involve violent crimes. What about all those people looking at crime
scene photos and autopsy images? Are they all just supposed to go home and
pretend it never happened?

What did you find out when you started reporting?

In one study, about 50 percent of jurors who served on difficult cases showed
trauma-related symptoms like sleeplessness, intrusive thoughts or anxiety.
Another recent study found that even participants in a mock murder trial
experienced a fourfold increase in PTSD symptoms after viewing skeletal remains.
Mental health experts have a name for this: ‚Äúvicarious trauma‚Äù or ‚Äúsecondary
traumatic stress.‚Äù Yet historically, courts have provided jurors with virtually
no support.

What kinds of cases are we talking about?

Any case involving disturbing, graphic evidence ‚Äî murders, sexual assaults,
child abuse, violent crimes. Chloe Beck, whom I interviewed, served on the trial
of a nanny accused of stabbing two children to death. She told me she still sees
those crime scene images years later: ‚ÄúThe little orange toothbrush hanging on
the wall ‚Äî covered in blood.‚Äù She hasn‚Äôt had kids yet, partly because the
thought of needing child care terrifies her.

One judge brought in a therapy dog to help jurors.

Jill Karofsky, the chief justice of the Wisconsin Supreme Court, has been a
pioneer in recognizing this problem. During one trial involving child
pornography, jurors were so physically sick from the evidence that she had to
keep wastebaskets nearby. She started small ‚Äî bringing in a therapy dog during
lunch breaks, writing a personal letter to jurors with information about trauma
reactions. She arranged free counseling with a therapist friend.

Do people try to beg off jury duty if they‚Äôre squeamish? Do judges let them?

People definitely try. During jury selection for my case, a mother of four
daughters said she couldn‚Äôt be impartial. But the judge, understandably, didn‚Äôt
excuse everyone who felt shaken. If you exclude everyone who might be affected,
then we‚Äôd have no juries. Our justice system requires ordinary people to grapple
with others‚Äô crimes, no matter how difficult it may be.

People in government are starting to recognize the problem.

Yes, slowly. Philadelphia just launched a program offering the same type of
counseling that first responders use. North Dakota and Massachusetts have
programs, too. But most jurisdictions offer nothing beyond a thank-you and a
small payment.

DRUG DISGUISE
An array of brightly colored cannabis gummies. [https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/04/07/multimedia/10themorning-nl-cannabis/10themorning-nl-cannabis-jumbo.jpg]
Weed gummies.Tony Cenicola/The New York TimesThe recent boom in edible marijuana
products is hurting kids, according to a new investigation by The Times. 
Danielle Ivory, who reported the article with Julie Tate and Megan Twohey,
explains the findings.

Fourth graders unwittingly ate a parent‚Äôs weed gummies. A toddler consumed a
mislabeled THC cake pop. Another child mistook a cannabis cookie for a regular
baked good. All were rushed to the hospital with alarming symptoms.

Millions of Americans use cannabis without issues. But as legal access to
marijuana has expanded, the number of poisonings related to the drug has sharply
increased, especially among kids.

 * Last year, more than 22,000 cannabis exposures were reported to poison
   centers in the United States, up from about 930 in 2009. Most involved
   children or teens and were deemed accidents.
 * Most cases aren‚Äôt severe. But a growing number have led to life-threatening
   consequences like breathing problems. Last year, more than 100 required
   ventilators.
 * Our reporting identified dozens of children across the country who had
   consumed cannabis products from stashes belonging to relatives or friends and
   were hospitalized with symptoms of poisoning. At least 38 cannabis-related
   poisoning cases have led to charges filed against parents and other
   caregivers.

‚ÄúPeople Like Us,‚Äù by Jason Mott: In Mott‚Äôs worthy follow-up to his National Book
Award-winning ‚ÄúHell of a Book,‚Äù a Black writer on a plane introduces himself to
his seatmate as Ta-Nehisi Coates. ‚ÄúTurns out I can be anyone you want me to be
if I‚Äôm just willing to say the words,‚Äù he tells the reader. The novel unfolds in
this spirit, following two writers down very different paths through a world
rived by racism, gun violence and their own personal crises. Because Mott is at
the wheel, the tour is wickedly witty, full of snide asides about the publishing
industry, and so timely and close to home you won‚Äôt know whether to close your
window or stick your head out for a better view. Either way, you won‚Äôt forget
